<br>
TODAY The Courier-Mail begins publication of the Apollo 11 astronauts' own stories of their historic voyage to the moon.<br>
<br>
First to tell the tale is the &quot;Third Man,&quot; Michael Collins, who orbited the moon alone in the command module Columbia, while Neil Armstrong and Edwin (&quot;Buzz&quot;) Aldrin carried out their moon landing mission in the lunar module Eagle.<br>
<br>
These first-hand descriptions are exclusive to The Courier Mail.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>&quot;I got really excited&quot; - to see Eagle coming up. Collins tells of tense moments in historic flight.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Trying to cram eight days and nearly 500,000 miles into a couple of columns of print is a formidable job.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
I saw many things which human eyes are rarely privileged to see. But of all these it was the most wonderful thing to see Eagle coming up from the surface of the moon.<br>
I really got excited then because for the first time it was clear that they had done it. They had landed on the moon and got off again.<br>
It was a nice, clear, crisp lunar day, if there is such a thing. The moon didn't look sinister or forbidding, as it can at very low sun angles.<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>But that day, with a high sun angle, it was a happy place. It also was a happy situation, because here was the LM (Lunar Module), getting larger and larger, brighter and shinier, and right dab smack where it should have been.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Tricky.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
All the tricky parts of the rendezvous were over, and now all we had to do was dock and get home. <br>
The computer, of course, had been telling me that everything was going well, but that's a rather impersonal message.<br>
It's not any substitute for being able to look out the window and really see Eagle fixed in the reticle pattern as if riding on railroad tracks. <br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Neil Armstrong made the initial manoeuvres to get up close. I took over the docking at a distance of 20 or 30 feet.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
It's just easier to do from my side, since he's looking over his head out through a small window and I'm looking straight ahead through a larger window.<br>
The docking process begins when the two vehicles touch and the probe slides into the drogue.<br>
They're held together then by three tiny capture latches, and it's almost like paperclips holding together two vehicles, one of which weighs 30,000lb. and the other 5,000.<br>
It's a tenuous grasp. To make the combination rigid you fire a little gas bottle that activates a plunger which literally sucks the two vehicles together.<br>
At this point the tiny latches fire mechanically and you are held together by 12 very strong capture latches like monkey wrenches, that's the hard dock.<br>
Just as I fired the charge on the gas bottle we got a quite abnormal oscillation in the yaw axis.<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>We had 8 or 10 rather dubious seconds, then, when I really thought we were outside the boundaries for a successful retract, and that I was going to have to release the LM and go back and dock all over again.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
I could have done it, as there was plenty of fuel. I've heard that I said,&quot; all hell broke loose&quot;. I don't remember saying that, but if it's on the transcript of communications,  then I guess I did say it.<br>
At any rate, I instantly took action to correct the angle and so did Neil in Eagle.<br>
Together we returned the two vehicles to an in-line position. All this time the automatic retract cycle was taking place, and we heard a loud bang, which is characteristic of those 12 big latches slamming home. And lo and behold we were docked, and it was all over.<br>
The first thing I had to do then was get the tunnel cleared to remove the hatch and the probe and the drogue and to stow them.<br>
Then I floated up into the tunnel to greet them. I could see them both, those beady little eyes up there in the LM, and it's terrible but I can't remember now which one of them was first to get back into Columbia with me.<br>
I met them both in the tunnel and we shook hands, hard, and that was it.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Glad.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
I was glad to see them and they allowed as how they were happy to be back.<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>They passed the rock boxes through to me and handled them as if they were absolutely jampacked with rare jewels, which in a sense they were.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
I traded them for my old canisters (air purification canisters carried aboard the spacecraft) on a one for one basis and I've never been so glad to see lithium hydroxide boxes go and rock boxes come.<br>
They looked like something you'd expect to see stuffed way off in a corner of a bank vault.<br>
I was overjoyed at the idea that not only had this first mission succeeded in putting men on the moon, but beyond that we had the fantastic extra dividend of returning things of immense scientific value as well.<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>The flight in general was just beautiful. I was a little surprised by the initial ride on Saturn 5. It was rough for the first 15 seconds or so.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
I suppose Saturns are like people, in a way. No two are exactly the same. Ours seemed very busy.<br>
It was like a nervous lady driving her car down a narrow alley, unable to decide whether she's too far to the left or too far to the right - but she knows she's one or the other.<br>
So she keeps jerking the wheel back and forth.<br>
I expect that when I examine the data I'll find that my heightened awareness of these tense moments has made me exaggerate outrageously. But that's the way it felt.<br>
I was very glad when they called &quot;tower clear,&quot; because it was nice to know there was no structure around when this thing was going through its little hiccups and bumps.<br>
It was not as noisy as I expected, and we had no indications of any malfunctions.<br>
After about 15 seconds it quietened down and the second stage was absolutely as smooth as glass. It had a sort of ethereal quality. You couldn't believe you had those big engines burning behind you.<br>
During the third stage we picked up a more normal rocket-engine sensation, that of a very mild high-frequency oscillation or buzzing.<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Any flight like this is an extremely long, fragile daisy-chain of events.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
The malfunction of any one of thousands of pieces of hardware on the way could ruin the remainder of the mission.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Weak Link?</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I'm stopping there guys. I'm about half way through copying this and I doubt it will fit into one post but I'll see what happens. My fingers are tired. I'm not used to so much typing. If the paragraphs look short it's because I'm copying the whole thing out as it's written and there are six narrow columns. I'll finish it tomorrow and then start on Buzz Aldrin's story.<br>
<br>
