 Several topics, but I got really aggravated, &amp; couldn't get through on the phones...<br>
Some idiot was talking about various clues that the Lunar Landings were hoaxed. Now I don't want to go into all the ways this is nuts on this thread -it's in other places.<br>
 Art was vacilating, as the host of a conspiracy/fringe talk show must. He said that the felt that it happened, because he grew up before it happened, and he saw it all as it was going on (appealing here to the mainstream who doesn't go in for the hoax theories), but saying that this guy had some good points, and some really hard stuff to think over (appealing to the theorists, to keep the connspiracy alive, to keep his ratings up).<br>
I wanted to call in to tear this guy a new bodily orifice (with facts, and counters to their &quot;evidence&quot; and to point people listening to the many good sites trashing the hoax theories).<br>
<br>
One of his points was that the third man on each flight was alone in the CM for a long time, going around the backside of the Moon. They were alone the way no one in history before or since has been, and it must have been a tansforming experience. Isn't it suspicious, he asked, that we haven't heard anything from these 6 men, who were supposedly in the CM?<br>
<br>
It's interesting to hear what Collins had to say. He was busy, or glad of the quiet to sleep(!), or eager to catch up on what he missed all the time he was out of contact with the LEM.<br>
 A professional aviatior; it was just another flight, alone in a cockpit, worrying about the mission,  eager to get it done right and get home.<br>
<br>
<br>
And I bet it was a transforming experience. I've heard from many people who've been up there, and almost nobody is unaffected by being in space.<br>
Note what Collins said about wishing that we'd find wys to use our ability to travel in space to make things better on Earth and to preserve it.<br>
 Remember that when some nincompoop drags out the old &quot;Disposable Earth&quot; argument against going into space: &quot;Oh sure, we'll just go into space to rape all the other planets after we're done raping and ruining this one&quot;.<br>
 The only places I've heard this from are people who haven't heard about the real possibilities of going into space, don't like or trust it on the surface (because technology and industry must be wrong and harmful, right?), and automatically decide they can't agree with me on it being a good thig for us to do.<br>
 The &quot;Disposable Earth&quot; theory has never seriously come from anyone knowledgeable about space and in favor of it (to my experience), and  I'm willing to bet money right now it has most certainly never <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">ever</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> come from somebody who's been in space.<br>
 Quite the reverse.<br>
Hardened test pilot combat veterans have been known to just go silent for minutes at a time, staring out the window, composing poetry even, or even sniffling back tears over the sight.<br>
I never fail to stomp on this whenever I run into it. I make sure that the people who think this could possiblty be in anybody's thinking change their mind -if not about space, at least about people who might be in favor of going into space- before I'm done. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A> at: 2/7/04 4:20 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nintendonick>NintendoNick</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 65<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/7/04 7:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1003.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Moon Men's Own Stories...</span><hr size=1> You are so right. I think if everyone could travel in space we would become a more enlightened species. To see the world from so far away and not be changed by the experience you would have to have marshmallow between your ears. To see the infinity of space up close and endure the months of travelling through empty void would wake up even the most stupid of technophobes. We are but a grain of sand on the beach and all our science is nothing compared to the power of nature. I think colonising space would help us to appreciate the earth. Some people might enjoy the tranquility of a new frontier but many will return to earth homesick and with new respect for it. <br>
